### Describe the bug

Summary: In some situations, the data sent by the [DynamoDB table resource's `BatchWriter`](https://boto3.amazonaws.com/v1/documentation/api/latest/reference/services/dynamodb.html#DynamoDB.Table.batch_writer) is invalid because some elements are serialized twice.

This may be the same underlying issue as https://github.com/boto/boto3/issues/3474 (to be confirmed by the reporter there)

### Expected Behavior

All items should be serialized once, like `item2` in the repro example.

### Current Behavior

Repeated items get double-serialized, resulting in incorrect data, like `item1` in the repro example.

### Reproduction Steps

To reproduce, consider the following example:

```python
import boto3

table_name = "test-double-serialization-tbl"
dynamodb = boto3.resource('dynamodb')
table = dynamodb.Table(table_name)

item1 = {
    "test-double-serialization-pk": "0",
    "test-double-serialization-sk": "2022-11-03T11:00:00+00:00",
    "val": {"a": 1, "b": 11},
}

item2 = {
    "test-double-serialization-pk": "1",
    "test-double-serialization-sk": "2022-11-03T11:00:00+00:00",
    "val": {"a": 2, "b": 22},
}

items = [item1, item2, item1]

with table.batch_writer() as writer:
    for item in items:
        writer.put_item(Item=item)
```

This will fail with this error:

```
An error occurred (ValidationException) when calling the BatchWriteItem operation: The provided key element does not match the schema
```

Using the debug-level logger, we can inspect the data to observe that the request contains the following body. Note the difference in serialization between the (correct) middle element versus the (incorrect) other two:

```json
{
    "RequestItems": {
        "test-double-serialization-tbl": [
            {
                "PutRequest": {
                    "Item": {
                        "test-double-serialization-pk": {
                            "M": {"S": {"S": "0"}}
                        },
                        "test-double-serialization-sk": {
                            "M": {"S": {"S": "2022-11-03T11:00:00+00:00"}}
                        },
                        "val": {
                            "M": {
                                "M": {
                                    "M": {
                                        "a": {"M": {"N": {"S": "1"}}},
                                        "b": {"M": {"N": {"S": "11"}}},
                                    }
                                }
                            }
                        },
                    }
                }
            },
            {
                "PutRequest": {
                    "Item": {
                        "test-double-serialization-pk": {"S": "1"},
                        "test-double-serialization-sk": {
                            "S": "2022-11-03T11:00:00+00:00"
                        },
                        "val": {"M": {"a": {"N": "2"}, "b": {"N": "22"}}},
                    }
                }
            },
            {
                "PutRequest": {
                    "Item": {
                        "test-double-serialization-pk": {
                            "M": {"S": {"S": "0"}}
                        },
                        "test-double-serialization-sk": {
                            "M": {"S": {"S": "2022-11-03T11:00:00+00:00"}}
                        },
                        "val": {
                            "M": {
                                "M": {
                                    "M": {
                                        "a": {"M": {"N": {"S": "1"}}},
                                        "b": {"M": {"N": {"S": "11"}}},
                                    }
                                }
                            }
                        },
                    }
                }
            },
        ]
    }
}
```

The incorrect double-serialization is caused by this behavior of Python:

```python
used_twice = {'x': 1, 'y':2}
item1 = {'foo': used_twice, 'bar': 3}
item2 = {'foo': used_twice, 'bar': 4}
item1['foo']['x'] = 9
assert item1['foo']['x'] == 9
assert item2['foo']['x'] == 9
```

In boto3, this pattern occured [here](https://github.com/boto/boto3/blob/61de529b5f9a7bdcc8c76debb472a7f934d048e6/boto3/dynamodb/transform.py#L316) whenever the DynamoDB-resource-specific `ParameterTransformer` operates on a data structure when a dict contains at least one member of shape `AttributeValue` and is used twice in the same _containing data structure_. Sameness can be determined using [Python's id() function](https://docs.python.org/3.8/library/functions.html#id). In the repro example above, the "containing data structure" is the complete content of the batched request.

Additional incorrect double serialization may also arise when using expression attributes or condition expressions due to similar code patterns in [`TransformationInjector`](https://github.com/boto/boto3/blob/61de529b5f9a7bdcc8c76debb472a7f934d048e6/boto3/dynamodb/transform.py#L129-L222) and [`ConditionExpressionTransformation`](https://github.com/boto/boto3/blob/61de529b5f9a7bdcc8c76debb472a7f934d048e6/boto3/dynamodb/transform.py#L225-L261). I did not attempt a reproduction of these.


